Well, this should open up a new can of worms for discussions.  It is documented that for every &quot;grunt&quot; in the bush, that it took seven support people in base to support him.  These are the folks who got your ammo, food, mail, clothes, medical help, avgas, and tracked your pay.  <br>
Yes, we all have feelings for those who screwed up those things.  But what about the positives?  Ever seen anyone on the site who admitted to being a cook? A M.P.?  A Mail clerk? A Payroll clerk?<br>
Did they all work the bush? Did we all become killers, outcasts, and renegades because of our work in the bush?  Our was it enough to become those things by turning our in country &quot;survival skills&quot; into todays &quot;coping skills&quot;?<br><br>
Me first, I started this thread.  I was a Battalion Radio Repairman.  I humped and repaired radios out to the forward firebases.  My outfit was &quot;always&quot; at forward firebases because we were Self-propelled (tracked) 8 inch artillery.  I did not live at the forward firebases.  I do have 3 battle stars on my service ribbon. These are presented for 30 days continious in the field.  I guess this means not in my Hdqrs. Battery repairing radios.  I did two tours. <br>
 <br>
I did burn shit, serve k.p., guard duty, perimeter duty.  I have survived numerous motarings. A regular Saturday nite festival in An Khe. I slept in a tent.  I fired my rifle to kill.  I don't know if I killed anyone.  I saw dead bodies. I was assigned to Hdqrs. Battery.  Base camp An Khe.<br><br>
The hardest thing for me to swallow was being called a &quot;REMF&quot; in a group counseling meeting.  Later I learned that my job was valuable and that not all of us got to be like John Wayne.  All the guys in my squad made it home.  So those were the positives.<br><br>
Who else?  Do you think you are a REMF?  Do you wish you weren't?  Isn't it just enough that WE were in Vietnam?  Do we still seperate each other as to how much blood we spilled or gave?  Do we still think of ourselves as more of a Vietnam vet if we were in the bush as opposed to being in a support role?  The hard thing is to find value in what we did to offset all those things that we lost.<br><br>
Comments?
